INSERT INTO `topics` VALUES (1,'Design tables for storing data','Structure tables to hold information efficiently.','# Design Tables for Storing Data\n\nDesigning effective tables is the foundation of database development. Well-structured tables ensure data integrity, performance, and maintainability.\n\n## Key Principles:\n\n**Atomic Values**: Each column should contain only one piece of information\n**Appropriate Naming**: Use clear, descriptive names for tables and columns\n**Data Types**: Choose the most specific data type for each column\n**Constraints**: Implement constraints to enforce data validity\n\n## Table Design Process:\n\n1. **Identify Entities**: Determine what objects need to be stored\n2. **Define Attributes**: List all properties for each entity\n3. **Establish Relationships**: Determine how entities relate to each other\n4. **Apply Normalization**: Organize to minimize redundancy\n\n## Best Practices:\n\n- Use singular nouns for table names (Customer, not Customers)\n- Include primary key in every table\n- Avoid reserved words for names\n- Document table purposes and relationships\n- Consider future growth and changes\n\n## Common Patterns:\n\n**Lookup Tables**: For standardized values (status types, categories)\n**Junction Tables**: For many-to-many relationships\n**Audit Tables**: For tracking changes and history\n\n## Performance Considerations:\n\n- Estimate table growth rates\n- Plan for indexing strategy\n- Consider partitioning for large tables\n- Archive historical data separately\n\n## Example Structure:\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE employees (\n    employee_id INT PRIMARY KEY,\n    first_name VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL,\n    last_name VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL,\n    email VARCHAR(100) UNIQUE,\n    hire_date DATE NOT NULL,\n    department_id INT,\n    salary DECIMAL(10,2) CHECK (salary >= 0)\n);\n```',1,45,45,'text'),(2,'Identify appropriate primary key','Choose a unique column to identify each record.','# Identify Appropriate Primary Key\n\nThe primary key uniquely identifies each record in a table and is fundamental to relational database design.\n\n## Characteristics of Good Primary Keys:\n\n**Uniqueness**: Must uniquely identify each row\n**Non-null**: Cannot contain NULL values\n**Stability**: Should not change over time\n**Simplicity**: Preferably short and simple\n\n## Types of Primary Keys:\n\n**Natural Keys**: Based on existing business data (email, SSN)\n**Surrogate Keys**: Artificially created identifiers (auto-increment IDs)\n**Composite Keys**: Multiple columns combined for uniqueness\n\n## Selection Criteria:\n\n- Choose keys that are inherently unique\n- Prefer numeric over string keys for performance\n- Avoid using business data that might change\n- Consider foreign key relationships\n\n## Best Practices:\n\n- Use surrogate keys for most tables\n- Keep primary keys as small as possible\n- Use consistent naming conventions (id, _id)\n- Document the reasoning behind key choices\n\n## Performance Implications:\n\n- Primary keys are automatically indexed\n- Integer keys perform better than string keys\n- Composite keys can be less efficient\n- GUIDs/UUIDs can cause index fragmentation\n\n## Example Choices:\n```sql\n-- Natural key (if emails are guaranteed unique)\nCREATE TABLE users (\n    email VARCHAR(255) PRIMARY KEY,\n    -- other columns\n);\n\n-- Surrogate key (recommended)\nCREATE TABLE products (\n    product_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,\n    sku VARCHAR(20) UNIQUE NOT NULL,\n    -- other columns\n);\n\n-- Composite key (for junction tables)\nCREATE TABLE order_items (\n    order_id INT,\n    product_id INT,\n    quantity INT,\n    PRIMARY KEY (order_id, product_id)\n);\n```',1,30,30,'text'),(3,'Choose data types to meet requirements','Select the best data type for each column.','# Choose Data Types to Meet Requirements\n\nSelecting appropriate data types is crucial for data integrity, storage efficiency, and performance.\n\n## Common Data Type Categories:\n\n**Numeric Types**: INT, BIGINT, DECIMAL, FLOAT, DOUBLE\n**String Types**: CHAR, VARCHAR, TEXT, BLOB\n**Temporal Types**: DATE, TIME, DATETIME, TIMESTAMP\n**Specialized Types**: JSON, XML, Spatial, Boolean\n\n## Selection Guidelines:\n\n**Storage Considerations**:\n- Choose the smallest type that accommodates expected data\n- Use VARCHAR instead of CHAR for variable-length data\n- Prefer INT over BIGINT if values fit within range\n\n**Precision Requirements**:\n- Use DECIMAL for financial calculations\n- Choose appropriate precision for numeric types\n- Consider timezone requirements for temporal data\n\n**Performance Implications**:\n- Fixed-length types (CHAR) can be faster for some operations\n- Smaller data types reduce storage and improve cache efficiency\n- Indexed columns benefit from compact data types\n\n## Best Practices:\n\n1. **Be Specific**: Choose the most appropriate type\n2. **Plan for Growth**: Allow reasonable room for expansion\n3. **Consistency**: Use consistent types across related tables\n4. **Documentation**: Document unusual type choices\n\n## Common Pitfalls:\n\n- Using VARCHAR for all string data\n- Storing numbers as strings\n- Ignoring timezone requirements\n- Underestimating maximum value sizes\n\n## Example Selections:\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE financial_records (\n    record_id INT PRIMARY KEY,\n    -- Use DECIMAL for monetary values\n    amount DECIMAL(15, 2) NOT NULL,\n    -- VARCHAR for variable-length strings\n    description VARCHAR(255),\n    -- DATE for date-only values\n    transaction_date DATE NOT NULL,\n    -- TIMESTAMP for precise time recording\n    created_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,\n    -- BOOLEAN for true/false values\n    is_reconciled BOOLEAN DEFAULT FALSE\n);\n```',1,30,30,'text'),(4,'Design relationships between tables','Link tables logically with foreign keys.','# Design Relationships Between Tables\n\nTable relationships define how data in different tables connects and interacts, forming the core of relational databases.\n\n## Relationship Types:\n\n**One-to-One (1:1)**: Each record in Table A relates to one record in Table B\n**One-to-Many (1:M)**: Each record in Table A relates to many records in Table B\n**Many-to-Many (M:M)**: Records in Table A relate to many in Table B, and vice versa\n\n## Implementation:\n\n**Foreign Keys**: Columns that reference primary keys in other tables\n**Referential Integrity**: Ensures relationships remain valid\n**Cascade Operations**: Automatic updates/deletes across related tables\n\n## Design Considerations:\n\n**Cardinality**: Determine how many relationships exist\n**Optionality**: Identify whether relationships are mandatory or optional\n**Business Rules**: Ensure relationships reflect real-world constraints\n\n## Best Practices:\n\n- Use foreign key constraints to enforce relationships\n- Name foreign keys consistently (e.g., user_id, order_id)\n- Consider indexing foreign key columns\n- Document relationship purposes and rules\n\n## Performance Implications:\n\n- Join operations depend on relationship design\n- Proper indexing improves relationship query performance\n- Cascade operations can impact performance on large datasets\n\n## Example Relationships:\n```sql\n-- One-to-Many: One customer, many orders\nCREATE TABLE customers (\n    customer_id INT PRIMARY KEY,\n    name VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL\n);\n\nCREATE TABLE orders (\n    order_id INT PRIMARY KEY,\n    customer_id INT,\n    order_date DATE,\n    FOREIGN KEY (customer_id) REFERENCES customers(customer_id)\n);\n\n-- Many-to-Many: Students and Courses (using junction table)\nCREATE TABLE students (\n    student_id INT PRIMARY KEY,\n    name VARCHAR(100)\n);\n\nCREATE TABLE courses (\n    course_id INT PRIMARY KEY,\n    title VARCHAR(100)\n);\n\nCREATE TABLE student_courses (\n    student_id INT,\n    course_id INT,\n    enrollment_date DATE,\n    PRIMARY KEY (student_id, course_id),\n    FOREIGN KEY (student_id) REFERENCES students(student_id),\n    FOREIGN KEY (course_id) REFERENCES courses(course_id)\n);\n```',1,60,60,'text'),(5,'Normalize database','Organize data to reduce redundancy and improve integrity.','# Normalize Database\n\nNormalization is the process of organizing data to reduce redundancy and improve data integrity through a series of normal forms.\n\n## Normal Forms:\n\n**First Normal Form (1NF)**:\n- Eliminate repeating groups\n- Ensure atomic values\n- Identify primary key\n\n**Second Normal Form (2NF)**:\n- Meet 1NF requirements\n- Remove partial dependencies (all non-key attributes depend on entire primary key)\n\n**Third Normal Form (3NF)**:\n- Meet 2NF requirements\n- Remove transitive dependencies (non-key attributes don\'t depend on other non-key attributes)\n\n**Boyce-Codd Normal Form (BCNF)**:\n- Stricter version of 3NF\n- Every determinant must be a candidate key\n\n## Normalization Process:\n\n1. **Identify Functional Dependencies**: Determine how attributes relate\n2. **Eliminate Repeating Groups**: Create separate tables\n3. **Remove Partial Dependencies**: Ensure full functional dependency on primary key\n4. **Eliminate Transitive Dependencies**: Non-key attributes should depend only on the key\n\n## Benefits:\n\n- Reduced data redundancy\n- Improved data integrity\n- Easier maintenance\n- More flexible design\n\n## When to Denormalize:\n\n- Performance-critical applications\n- Read-heavy reporting systems\n- Data warehouse environments\n- Simple lookup scenarios\n\n## Example Normalization:\n```sql\n-- Unnormalized (all in one table)\nCREATE TABLE orders_unnormalized (\n    order_id INT,\n    customer_name VARCHAR(100),\n    customer_address VARCHAR(255),\n    product1_name VARCHAR(100),\n    product1_price DECIMAL(10,2),\n    product2_name VARCHAR(100),\n    product2_price DECIMAL(10,2)\n);\n\n-- Normalized (3NF)\nCREATE TABLE customers (\n    customer_id INT PRIMARY KEY,\n    name VARCHAR(100),\n    address VARCHAR(255)\n);\n\nCREATE TABLE products (\n    product_id INT PRIMARY KEY,\n    name VARCHAR(100),\n    price DECIMAL(10,2)\n);\n\nCREATE TABLE orders (\n    order_id INT PRIMARY KEY,\n    customer_id INT,\n    order_date DATE,\n    FOREIGN KEY (customer_id) REFERENCES customers(customer_id)\n);\n\nCREATE TABLE order_items (\n    order_id INT,\n    product_id INT,\n    quantity INT,\n    PRIMARY KEY (order_id, product_id),\n    FOREIGN KEY (order_id) REFERENCES orders(order_id),\n    FOREIGN KEY (product_id) REFERENCES products(product_id)\n);\n```',1,90,90,'text'),(6,'Data protection measures','Apply security and backup strategies to safeguard data.','# Data Protection Measures\n\nData protection encompasses strategies and techniques to safeguard database information from loss, corruption, or unauthorized access.\n\n## Protection Strategies:\n\n**Backup and Recovery**:\n- Regular full, differential, and transaction log backups\n- Tested recovery procedures\n- Off-site storage for disaster recovery\n\n**Access Control**:\n- Role-based permissions\n- Principle of least privilege\n- Regular access reviews\n\n**Encryption**:\n- Data-at-rest encryption\n- Data-in-transit encryption (SSL/TLS)\n- Column-level encryption for sensitive data\n\n## Security Measures:\n\n**Authentication**: Verify user identities\n**Authorization**: Control access to resources\n**Auditing**: Track database activities\n**Network Security**: Firewalls, VPNs, and secure connections\n\n## Best Practices:\n\n1. **Regular Backups**: Implement automated backup schedules\n2. **Access Management**: Grant minimum necessary permissions\n3. **Encryption**: Protect sensitive data at all stages\n4. **Monitoring**: Implement security monitoring and alerts\n5. **Patching**: Keep database software updated\n\n## Implementation Examples:\n```sql\n-- Role-based access control\nCREATE ROLE data_reader;\nGRANT SELECT ON ALL TABLES TO data_reader;\n\nCREATE ROLE data_writer;\nGRANT INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE ON ALL TABLES TO data_writer;\n\n-- Column-level encryption (SQL Server example)\nCREATE MASTER KEY ENCRYPTION BY PASSWORD = \'StrongPassword123!\';\nCREATE CERTIFICATE MyCertificate WITH SUBJECT = \'Protect Sensitive Data\';\nCREATE SYMMETRIC KEY MySymmetricKey \n    WITH ALGORITHM = AES_256 \n    ENCRYPTION BY CERTIFICATE MyCertificate;\n\n-- Backup strategies\n-- Full backup weekly\nBACKUP DATABASE MyDatabase TO DISK = \'C:BackupsMyDatabase_Full.bak\';\n\n-- Differential backup daily\nBACKUP DATABASE MyDatabase TO DISK = \'C:BackupsMyDatabase_Diff.bak\' \n    WITH DIFFERENTIAL;\n\n-- Transaction log backup hourly\nBACKUP LOG MyDatabase TO DISK = \'C:BackupsMyDatabase_Log.trn\';\n```',1,60,60,'text'),(7,'Create, alter, and drop tables','Manage the structure of database tables.','# Create, Alter, and Drop Tables\n\nDDL (Data Definition Language) commands manage table structures, allowing creation, modification, and removal of database tables.\n\n## CREATE TABLE Syntax:\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE table_name (\n    column1 datatype constraints,\n    column2 datatype constraints,\n    ...\n    table_constraints\n);\nCommon Column Constraints:\nPRIMARY KEY: Uniquely identifies each row\n\nFOREIGN KEY: Links to primary key in another table\n\nNOT NULL: Ensures column cannot contain NULL values\n\nUNIQUE: Ensures all values in column are different\n\nCHECK: Ensures values meet specific conditions\n\nDEFAULT: Sets default value for column\n\nALTER TABLE Operations:\nAdd, modify, or drop columns\n\nAdd or drop constraints\n\nChange data types or column properties\n\nRename tables or columns\n\nDROP TABLE Considerations:\nPermanently removes table and all data\n\nRequires appropriate permissions\n\nMay fail if foreign key constraints exist\n\nBest Practices:\nPlanning: Design tables carefully before creation\n\nTesting: Test alterations in development environment first\n\nBackup: Backup data before major structural changes\n\nDocumentation: Document schema changes and reasons\n\nVersion Control: Use migration scripts for changes\n\nExample Operations:\nsql\n-- Create table with constraints\nCREATE TABLE employees (\n    employee_id INT PRIMARY KEY,\n    first_name VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL,\n    last_name VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL,\n    email VARCHAR(100) UNIQUE,\n    hire_date DATE DEFAULT CURRENT_DATE,\n    salary DECIMAL(10,2) CHECK (salary >= 0),\n    department_id INT,\n    FOREIGN KEY (department_id) REFERENCES departments(department_id)\n);\n\n-- Alter table to add new column\nALTER TABLE employees ADD COLUMN phone_number VARCHAR(15);\n\n-- Alter table to modify column\nALTER TABLE employees ALTER COLUMN phone_number SET DATA TYPE VARCHAR(20);\n\n-- Alter table to add constraint\nALTER TABLE employees ADD CONSTRAINT chk_salary_range \n    CHECK (salary BETWEEN 30000 AND 200000);\n\n-- Drop table (with caution!)\nDROP TABLE employees CASCADE;\n```',2,60,60,'text'),(8,'Create, alter, and drop views','Build and modify virtual tables for queries.','# Create, Alter, and Drop Views\n\nViews are virtual tables that provide customized perspectives of data without storing the data themselves.\n\n## View Types:\n\n**Simple Views**: Based on a single table with no functions\n**Complex Views**: Incorporate multiple tables, functions, or grouping\n**Materialized Views**: Physically store result sets (varies by RDBMS)\n**Indexed Views**: Materialized views with indexes (SQL Server)\n\n## CREATE VIEW Syntax:\n```sql\nCREATE VIEW view_name AS\nSELECT column1, column2, ...\nFROM table_name\nWHERE condition;\nBenefits of Views:\nSecurity: Restrict access to specific columns or rows\nSimplification: Hide complex queries from users\nConsistency: Provide standardized data access\nAbstraction: Shield applications from schema changes\n\nALTER VIEW Operations:\nModify the underlying SELECT statement\n\nChange view properties or metadata\n\nAdd or remove columns from view definition\n\nDROP VIEW Considerations:\nRemoves view definition but not underlying data\n\nDependent objects may be affected\n\nRequires appropriate permissions\n\nBest Practices:\nNaming: Use clear, descriptive names for views\n\nDocumentation: Document view purposes and usage\n\nPerformance: Be mindful of view performance implications\n\nSecurity: Use views for row-level and column-level security\n\nTesting: Test views with various data scenarios\n\nExample View Operations:\nsql\n-- Create a simple view\nCREATE VIEW active_customers AS\nSELECT customer_id, first_name, last_name, email\nFROM customers\nWHERE status = \'active\';\n\n-- Create a complex view with joins\nCREATE VIEW order_summary AS\nSELECT \n    o.order_id,\n    o.order_date,\n    c.first_name || \' \' || c.last_name AS customer_name,\n    COUNT(oi.product_id) AS item_count,\n    SUM(oi.quantity * oi.unit_price) AS total_amount\nFROM orders o\nJOIN customers c ON o.customer_id = c.customer_id\nJOIN order_items oi ON o.order_id = oi.order_id\nGROUP BY o.order_id, o.order_date, c.first_name, c.last_name;\n\n-- Alter a view (redefine it)\nCREATE OR REPLACE VIEW active_customers AS\nSELECT customer_id, first_name, last_name, email, phone\nFROM customers\nWHERE status = \'active\' AND last_login_date > CURRENT_DATE - 30;\n\n-- Drop a view\nDROP VIEW order_summary;\n```',2,45,45,'text'),(9,'Stored procedures and functions','Automate tasks with reusable SQL routines.','# Stored Procedures and Functions\n\nStored procedures and functions are essential database objects that encapsulate SQL code for reuse, security, and performance.\n\n## Stored Procedures:\n**Characteristics**:\n- Can contain multiple SQL statements\n- Support input and output parameters\n- Can return multiple result sets\n- Allow transaction control\n- Support error handling\n\n**Benefits**:\n- Code reusability and maintenance\n- Enhanced security (grant execute without direct table access)\n- Reduced network traffic\n- Performance improvement (compiled and cached)\n\n**Creation Syntax**:\n```sql\nCREATE PROCEDURE procedure_name (@param1 DATATYPE, @param2 DATATYPE OUTPUT)\nAS\nBEGIN\n    -- SQL statements\n    -- Business logic\nEND\n```\n\n## Functions:\n**Characteristics**:\n- Must return a single value (scalar) or table\n- Can have input parameters\n- Cannot modify database state (with exceptions)\n- Deterministic or non-deterministic\n\n**Types**:\n- Scalar functions (return single value)\n- Table-valued functions (return table)\n- System functions (built-in)\n\n**Creation Syntax**:\n```sql\nCREATE FUNCTION function_name (@param DATATYPE)\nRETURNS RETURN_DATATYPE\nAS\nBEGIN\n    RETURN (SELECT value FROM table)\nEND\n```\n\n## Best Practices:\n- Use meaningful names\n- Include error handling\n- Avoid unnecessary complexity\n- Document parameters and purpose\n- Consider performance implications\n\n## Example Usage:\n```sql\n-- Stored procedure example\nCREATE PROCEDURE GetCustomerOrders @CustomerID INT\nAS\nBEGIN\n    SELECT * FROM Orders WHERE CustomerID = @CustomerID\nEND\n\n-- Function example\nCREATE FUNCTION CalculateDiscount (@Amount DECIMAL(10,2))\nRETURNS DECIMAL(10,2)\nAS\nBEGIN\n    RETURN CASE \n        WHEN @Amount > 1000 THEN @Amount * 0.1\n        ELSE 0\n    END\nEND\n```',2,90,90,'text'),(10,'Clustered vs. non-clustered indexes','Improve query performance with indexing strategies.','# Clustered vs. Non-Clustered Indexes\n\nIndexes are critical for database performance, and understanding the difference between clustered and non-clustered indexes is essential.\n\n## Clustered Index:\n**Characteristics**:\n- Determines physical order of data in table\n- Only one per table (the table itself is sorted)\n- Automatically created for primary key (usually)\n- Faster for range queries\n\n**Advantages**:\n- Excellent for range searches\n- No extra storage needed for data itself\n- Always covers queries for all columns\n\n**Disadvantages**:\n- Slower for insert/update/delete operations\n- Only one allowed per table\n\n## Non-Clustered Index:\n**Characteristics**:\n- Separate structure from data storage\n- Multiple allowed per table (up to 999 in SQL Server)\n- Contains pointer to actual data\n- Can include additional columns\n\n**Advantages**:\n- Faster for point queries\n- Multiple indexes for different query patterns\n- Less impact on write operations\n\n**Disadvantages**:\n- Extra storage required\n- May require bookmark lookups\n\n## Choosing Between Them:\n**Use Clustered Index For**:\n- Columns frequently used in range queries\n- Columns with sequential values\n- Primary key columns\n\n**Use Non-Clustered Index For**:\n- Columns frequently used in WHERE clauses\n- Columns used in JOIN conditions\n- Columns used in ORDER BY clauses\n\n## Example Implementation:\n```sql\n-- Clustered index (usually on primary key)\nCREATE CLUSTERED INDEX IX_Employees_EmployeeID \nON Employees (EmployeeID);\n\n-- Non-clustered index\nCREATE NONCLUSTERED INDEX IX_Employees_LastName \nON Employees (LastName);\n\n-- Non-clustered index with included columns\nCREATE NONCLUSTERED INDEX IX_Orders_CustomerID \nON Orders (CustomerID) \nINCLUDE (OrderDate, TotalAmount);\n```',2,60,60,'text'),(11,'JOINs (INNER, LEFT, RIGHT, CROSS, FULL, self joins)','Combine data across multiple tables.','# JOIN Operations\n\nJOIN operations combine rows from two or more tables based on related columns, enabling complex data retrieval across multiple tables.\n\n## JOIN Types:\n\n**INNER JOIN**:\n- Returns only matching rows from both tables\n- Most common JOIN type\n- Excludes non-matching rows\n\n**LEFT JOIN (LEFT OUTER JOIN)**:\n- Returns all rows from left table\n- Returns matching rows from right table\n- NULL values for non-matching right table rows\n\n**RIGHT JOIN (RIGHT OUTER JOIN)**:\n- Returns all rows from right table\n- Returns matching rows from left table\n- NULL values for non-matching left table rows\n\n**FULL JOIN (FULL OUTER JOIN)**:\n- Returns all rows when there\'s a match in either table\n- NULL values for non-matching rows on either side\n\n**CROSS JOIN**:\n- Returns Cartesian product of both tables\n- Each row from first table combined with each row from second table\n- Can generate large result sets\n\n**SELF JOIN**:\n- Regular join but table is joined with itself\n- Useful for hierarchical data or comparing rows within same table\n- Requires table aliases\n\n## Syntax Examples:\n```sql\n-- INNER JOIN\nSELECT orders.order_id, customers.customer_name\nFROM orders\nINNER JOIN customers ON orders.customer_id = customers.customer_id;\n\n-- LEFT JOIN\nSELECT employees.name, departments.department_name\nFROM employees\nLEFT JOIN departments ON employees.department_id = departments.department_id;\n\n-- RIGHT JOIN\nSELECT employees.name, departments.department_name\nFROM employees\nRIGHT JOIN departments ON employees.department_id = departments.department_id;\n\n-- FULL JOIN\nSELECT employees.name, departments.department_name\nFROM employees\nFULL JOIN departments ON employees.department_id = departments.department_id;\n\n-- CROSS JOIN\nSELECT products.product_name, suppliers.supplier_name\nFROM products\nCROSS JOIN suppliers;\n\n-- SELF JOIN\nSELECT e1.name AS employee_name, e2.name AS manager_name\nFROM employees e1\nLEFT JOIN employees e2 ON e1.manager_id = e2.employee_id;\n```\n\n## Performance Considerations:\n- Index foreign key columns used in JOIN conditions\n- Be mindful of JOIN order in complex queries\n- Use appropriate JOIN types to avoid unnecessary data retrieval\n- Consider query execution plans for optimization\n\n## Best Practices:\n- Use explicit JOIN syntax rather than implicit (comma-separated)\n- Always specify JOIN conditions\n- Use table aliases for readability\n- Test JOIN queries with different data volumes\n- Consider using EXISTS instead of JOIN for existence checks',3,120,120,'text'),(12,'UNION and INTERSECT','Merge results from multiple queries.','# UNION and INTERSECT Operations\n\nUNION and INTERSECT are set operations that combine results from multiple SELECT statements.\n\n## UNION:\n**Purpose**:\n- Combines result sets of two or more SELECT statements\n- Eliminates duplicate rows (use UNION ALL to keep duplicates)\n- Requires same number of columns in all SELECT statements\n- Requires compatible data types for corresponding columns\n\n**Syntax**:\n```sql\nSELECT column1, column2 FROM table1\nUNION\nSELECT column1, column2 FROM table2;\n```\n\n**UNION ALL**:\n- Faster than UNION (no duplicate removal)\n- Keeps all rows including duplicates\n- Use when duplicate rows are acceptable or desired\n\n## INTERSECT:\n**Purpose**:\n- Returns only rows that exist in both result sets\n- Similar to INNER JOIN but works on complete rows\n- Eliminates duplicate rows\n\n**Syntax**:\n```sql\nSELECT column1, column2 FROM table1\nINTERSECT\nSELECT column1, column2 FROM table2;\n```\n\n## EXCEPT (or MINUS in some databases):\n**Purpose**:\n- Returns rows from first query that aren\'t in second query\n- Useful for finding differences between result sets\n\n**Syntax**:\n```sql\nSELECT column1, column2 FROM table1\nEXCEPT\nSELECT column1, column2 FROM table2;\n```\n\n## Practical Examples:\n```sql\n-- Combine customers from two regions\nSELECT customer_name, city FROM customers_north\nUNION\nSELECT customer_name, city FROM customers_south;\n\n-- Find products available in both stores\nSELECT product_id FROM store1_inventory\nINTERSECT\nSELECT product_id FROM store2_inventory;\n\n-- Find customers who haven\'t placed orders\nSELECT customer_id FROM customers\nEXCEPT\nSELECT customer_id FROM orders;\n\n-- Combine with UNION ALL (keeping duplicates)\nSELECT product_name FROM current_products\nUNION ALL\nSELECT product_name FROM discontinued_products;\n```\n\n## Performance Considerations:\n- UNION/INTERSECT operations can be resource-intensive\n- Ensure columns in all SELECT statements have compatible data types\n- Use WHERE clauses to filter data before combining\n- Consider temporary tables for complex set operations\n\n## Best Practices:\n- Use meaningful column aliases in the first SELECT statement\n- Order the final result set with ORDER BY at the end\n- Test with small data sets before applying to large tables\n- Consider alternative approaches (JOINS, EXISTS) for better performance',3,60,60,'text'),(13,'DISTINCT, aliases, computed columns','Refine and customize result sets.','# DISTINCT, Aliases, and Computed Columns\n\nThese features enhance query readability and functionality by eliminating duplicates, providing meaningful names, and creating derived values.\n\n## DISTINCT Clause:\n**Purpose**:\n- Eliminates duplicate rows from result set\n- Can be applied to one or multiple columns\n- Returns only unique combinations of values\n\n**Syntax**:\n```sql\nSELECT DISTINCT column1, column2 FROM table_name;\n```\n\n**Considerations**:\n- DISTINCT operates on all selected columns\n- Can impact performance on large datasets\n- Use judiciously as it requires sorting\n\n## Column Aliases:\n**Purpose**:\n- Provide temporary names for columns or expressions\n- Improve readability of result sets\n- Essential when using computed columns\n\n**Syntax**:\n```sql\nSELECT column_name AS alias_name FROM table_name;\nSELECT column_name alias_name FROM table_name; -- AS is optional\n```\n\n**Best Practices**:\n- Use meaningful, descriptive aliases\n- Enclose aliases in quotes if they contain spaces or special characters\n- Maintain consistency in alias naming\n\n## Table Aliases:\n**Purpose**:\n- Provide temporary names for tables\n- Essential for self-joins and queries with multiple tables\n- Improve query readability and reduce typing\n\n**Syntax**:\n```sql\nSELECT a.column1, b.column2 \nFROM table1 a, table2 b \nWHERE a.id = b.foreign_id;\n```\n\n## Computed Columns:\n**Purpose**:\n- Create new values derived from existing columns\n- Perform calculations, concatenations, or transformations\n- Can use mathematical operators, functions, and constants\n\n**Syntax**:\n```sql\nSELECT column1, column2, (column1 * column2) AS calculated_value FROM table_name;\n```\n\n**Common Uses**:\n- Mathematical calculations (price * quantity)\n- String concatenation (first_name || \' \' || last_name)\n- Date calculations (CURRENT_DATE - birth_date)\n- Conditional logic with CASE statements\n\n## Practical Examples:\n```sql\n-- DISTINCT examples\nSELECT DISTINCT department FROM employees;\nSELECT DISTINCT city, state FROM customers;\n\n-- Alias examples\nSELECT first_name AS \"First Name\", last_name AS \"Last Name\" FROM employees;\nSELECT e.first_name, d.department_name \nFROM employees e \nJOIN departments d ON e.department_id = d.department_id;\n\n-- Computed column examples\nSELECT product_name, unit_price, quantity, (unit_price * quantity) AS total_value FROM order_details;\nSELECT first_name, last_name, (first_name || \' \' || last_name) AS full_name FROM customers;\nSELECT order_date, order_date + INTERVAL \'30 days\' AS due_date FROM orders;\nSELECT salary, \n       CASE \n           WHEN salary > 100000 THEN \'High\'\n           WHEN salary > 50000 THEN \'Medium\'\n           ELSE \'Low\'\n       END AS salary_level \nFROM employees;\n```\n\n## Performance Considerations:\n- Computed columns in SELECT don\'t affect storage\n- Consider persisted computed columns for frequently used calculations\n- DISTINCT can be expensive on large result sets\n- Proper indexing can improve DISTINCT performance',3,45,45,'text'),(14,'ORDER BY, WHERE, LIKE, BETWEEN, AND, OR, NOT, TOP/LIMIT, IN, ANY, ALL, NULL checks','Filter and sort query results effectively.','# Filtering and Sorting Data\n\nSQL provides powerful clauses and operators to filter and sort data, enabling precise control over query results.\n\n## WHERE Clause:\n**Purpose**:\n- Filters rows based on specified conditions\n- Applied before grouping and aggregation\n\n**Syntax**:\n```sql\nSELECT column1, column2 \nFROM table_name \nWHERE condition;\n```\n\n## Comparison Operators:\n- = Equal to\n- <> or != Not equal to\n- > Greater than\n- < Less than\n- >= Greater than or equal to\n- <= Less than or equal to\n\n## Logical Operators:\n**AND**:\n- Returns true if all conditions are true\n- Used to combine multiple conditions\n\n**OR**:\n- Returns true if any condition is true\n- Used for alternative conditions\n\n**NOT**:\n- Negates a condition\n- Returns true if condition is false\n\n## Special Operators:\n**LIKE**:\n- Pattern matching with wildcards\n- % matches any sequence of characters\n- _ matches any single character\n\n**BETWEEN**:\n- Range checking (inclusive)\n- Works with numbers, dates, and text\n\n**IN**:\n- Checks if value exists in a list\n- Alternative to multiple OR conditions\n\n**IS NULL / IS NOT NULL**:\n- Checks for NULL values\n- = NULL doesn\'t work for NULL comparisons\n\n**ANY/ALL**:\n- ANY: Returns true if any subquery values meet the condition\n- ALL: Returns true if all subquery values meet the condition\n\n## ORDER BY Clause:\n**Purpose**:\n- Sorts result set by specified columns\n- ASC for ascending (default), DESC for descending\n- Can sort by multiple columns\n\n## LIMIT/TOP Clause:\n**Purpose**:\n- Limits number of rows returned\n- TOP (SQL Server), LIMIT (MySQL, PostgreSQL), ROWNUM (Oracle)\n\n## Practical Examples:\n```sql\n-- Basic WHERE examples\nSELECT * FROM employees WHERE salary > 50000;\nSELECT * FROM products WHERE category = \'Electronics\';\n\n-- AND/OR examples\nSELECT * FROM customers WHERE city = \'New York\' AND age > 30;\nSELECT * FROM products WHERE category = \'Books\' OR category = \'Movies\';\n\n-- LIKE examples\nSELECT * FROM customers WHERE name LIKE \'J%\'; -- Names starting with J\nSELECT * FROM products WHERE description LIKE \'%wireless%\'; -- Contains wireless\n\n-- BETWEEN examples\nSELECT * FROM orders WHERE order_date BETWEEN \'2023-01-01\' AND \'2023-01-31\';\nSELECT * FROM products WHERE price BETWEEN 10 AND 50;\n\n-- IN examples\nSELECT * FROM customers WHERE city IN (\'New York\', \'London\', \'Tokyo\');\nSELECT * FROM orders WHERE status IN (\'Shipped\', \'Delivered\');\n\n-- NULL examples\nSELECT * FROM employees WHERE manager_id IS NULL;\nSELECT * FROM customers WHERE email IS NOT NULL;\n\n-- ORDER BY examples\nSELECT * FROM products ORDER BY price DESC;\nSELECT * FROM employees ORDER BY last_name ASC, first_name ASC;\n\n-- LIMIT/TOP examples\nSELECT TOP 10 * FROM products ORDER BY sales_count DESC; -- SQL Server\nSELECT * FROM customers LIMIT 5; -- MySQL, PostgreSQL\nSELECT * FROM orders WHERE ROWNUM <= 10; -- Oracle\n\n-- ANY/ALL examples\nSELECT * FROM products \nWHERE price > ANY (SELECT price FROM products WHERE category = \'Electronics\');\n\nSELECT * FROM employees \nWHERE salary > ALL (SELECT salary FROM employees WHERE department = \'Sales\');\n```\n\n## Performance Considerations:\n- Use indexes on columns frequently used in WHERE clauses\n- Avoid functions on indexed columns in WHERE clauses\n- Be cautious with LIKE patterns starting with wildcards (%)\n- Use EXPLAIN or similar tools to analyze query performance\n\n## Best Practices:\n- Use parentheses to clarify complex logical conditions\n- Consider using EXISTS instead of IN for subqueries\n- Use meaningful comparison values (avoid magic numbers)\n- Test queries with different data volumes',3,90,90,'text'),(15,'GROUP BY, HAVING, MIN, MAX, COUNT, AVG, SUM','Perform aggregation and summarize data.','# Aggregation and Grouping\n\nAggregate functions perform calculations on sets of values, returning a single value. GROUP BY and HAVING clauses organize and filter aggregated data.\n\n## Aggregate Functions:\n\n**COUNT()**:\n- Returns number of rows\n- COUNT(*) counts all rows\n- COUNT(column) counts non-NULL values in column\n\n**SUM()**:\n- Returns sum of values in numeric column\n- Ignores NULL values\n\n**AVG()**:\n- Returns average of values in numeric column\n- Ignores NULL values\n\n**MIN()**:\n- Returns minimum value in column\n- Works with numeric, date, and string columns\n\n**MAX()**:\n- Returns maximum value in column\n- Works with numeric, date, and string columns\n\n## GROUP BY Clause:\n**Purpose**:\n- Groups rows that have same values in specified columns\n- Enables aggregation per group rather than entire table\n- Often used with aggregate functions\n\n**Syntax**:\n```sql\nSELECT column1, aggregate_function(column2)\nFROM table_name\nGROUP BY column1;\n```\n\n## HAVING Clause:\n**Purpose**:\n- Filters groups based on aggregate conditions\n- Similar to WHERE but for groups rather than rows\n- Applied after GROUP BY\n\n**Syntax**:\n```sql\nSELECT column1, aggregate_function(column2)\nFROM table_name\nGROUP BY column1\nHAVING condition;\n```\n\n## Practical Examples:\n```sql\n-- Basic aggregate examples\nSELECT COUNT(*) AS total_employees FROM employees;\nSELECT AVG(salary) AS average_salary FROM employees;\nSELECT MAX(price) AS highest_price FROM products;\nSELECT MIN(stock_quantity) AS lowest_stock FROM inventory;\n\n-- GROUP BY examples\nSELECT department, COUNT(*) AS employee_count \nFROM employees \nGROUP BY department;\n\nSELECT category, AVG(price) AS average_price \nFROM products \nGROUP BY category;\n\nSELECT YEAR(order_date) AS order_year, SUM(total_amount) AS yearly_sales\nFROM orders \nGROUP BY YEAR(order_date);\n\n-- HAVING examples\nSELECT department, COUNT(*) AS employee_count \nFROM employees \nGROUP BY department \nHAVING COUNT(*) > 10;\n\nSELECT category, AVG(price) AS average_price \nFROM products \nGROUP BY category \nHAVING AVG(price) > 100;\n\nSELECT customer_id, COUNT(*) AS order_count \nFROM orders \nGROUP BY customer_id \nHAVING COUNT(*) >= 5;\n\n-- Multiple aggregates\nSELECT \n    department,\n    COUNT(*) AS employee_count,\n    AVG(salary) AS average_salary,\n    MIN(salary) AS min_salary,\n    MAX(salary) AS max_salary\nFROM employees \nGROUP BY department;\n\n-- GROUP BY multiple columns\nSELECT department, job_title, COUNT(*) AS employee_count\nFROM employees\nGROUP BY department, job_title;\n\n-- Using WHERE with GROUP BY\nSELECT department, AVG(salary) AS average_salary\nFROM employees\nWHERE hire_date > \'2020-01-01\'\nGROUP BY department;\n```\n\n## Performance Considerations:\n- Index columns used in GROUP BY clauses\n- Be mindful of grouping on columns with high cardinality\n- Consider filtering with WHERE before grouping to reduce data volume\n- Use EXPLAIN to analyze grouping performance\n\n## Common Pitfalls:\n- Including non-aggregated columns not in GROUP BY clause\n- Confusing WHERE (row filter) with HAVING (group filter)\n- Forgetting that COUNT(column) ignores NULL values\n- Overlooking the impact of NULL values in grouping columns\n\n## Best Practices:\n- Use meaningful aliases for aggregate columns\n- Consider the order of operations: WHERE → GROUP BY → HAVING → ORDER BY\n- Test queries with different data volumes\n- Document complex aggregation logic',3,90,90,'text'),(16,'INSERT INTO SELECT / VALUES','Add new rows of data.','# Inserting Data\n\nThe INSERT statement adds new rows to a table, using either explicit values or data from another table.\n\n## INSERT with VALUES:\n**Purpose**:\n- Adds one or more rows with specified values\n- Useful for adding static data\n\n**Syntax**:\n```sql\nINSERT INTO table_name (column1, column2, column3, ...)\nVALUES (value1, value2, value3, ...);\n\n-- Multiple rows\nINSERT INTO table_name (column1, column2, column3, ...)\nVALUES \n    (value1, value2, value3, ...),\n    (value4, value5, value6, ...),\n    ...;\n```\n\n## INSERT with SELECT:\n**Purpose**:\n- Adds rows based on result of SELECT statement\n- Useful for copying data between tables\n- Can transform data during insertion\n\n**Syntax**:\n```sql\nINSERT INTO table_name (column1, column2, column3, ...)\nSELECT column1, column2, column3, ...\nFROM source_table\nWHERE condition;\n```\n\n## Practical Examples:\n```sql\n-- Insert single row with VALUES\nINSERT INTO customers (first_name, last_name, email, phone)\nVALUES (\'John\', \'Doe\', \'john.doe@example.com\', \'555-1234\');\n\n-- Insert multiple rows with VALUES\nINSERT INTO products (product_name, category, price)\nVALUES \n    (\'Laptop\', \'Electronics\', 999.99),\n    (\'Desk Chair\', \'Furniture\', 149.99),\n    (\'Coffee Mug\', \'Kitchen\', 9.99);\n\n-- Insert with SELECT (copy data)\nINSERT INTO archived_orders (order_id, customer_id, order_date, total_amount)\nSELECT order_id, customer_id, order_date, total_amount\nFROM orders\nWHERE order_date < \'2022-01-01\';\n\n-- Insert with SELECT (transform data)\nINSERT INTO customer_summary (customer_id, total_orders, total_spent)\nSELECT \n    customer_id,\n    COUNT(*) AS total_orders,\n    SUM(total_amount) AS total_spent\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY customer_id;\n\n-- Insert with default values\nINSERT INTO settings (setting_name, setting_value)\nVALUES (\'theme\', DEFAULT);\n\n-- Insert with expressions\nINSERT INTO price_log (product_id, old_price, new_price, change_date)\nSELECT product_id, price, price * 1.1, CURRENT_DATE\nFROM products\nWHERE category = \'Electronics\';\n```\n\n## Special Considerations:\n\n**Identity/Auto-increment Columns**:\n- Typically don\'t need to be specified in INSERT\n- Database automatically generates values\n\n**Default Values**:\n- Use DEFAULT keyword to use column\'s default value\n- Omit column from column list to use default\n\n**NULL Values**:\n- Use NULL keyword to explicitly insert NULL\n- Omit column from column list to potentially get NULL\n\n**Constraints**:\n- INSERT must satisfy all constraints (NOT NULL, UNIQUE, FOREIGN KEY, etc.)\n- Violations will cause statement to fail\n\n## Performance Considerations:\n- Batch inserts (multiple VALUES) are faster than individual INSERT statements\n- For large data imports, consider bulk insert tools or temporary disabling indexes\n- Use transactions for multiple related INSERT statements\n\n## Error Handling:\n- Use try-catch blocks in applications\n- Check for constraint violations\n- Consider using INSERT IGNORE (MySQL) or ON CONFLICT (PostgreSQL) for handling duplicates\n\n## Best Practices:\n- Always specify column names for clarity and maintainability\n- Validate data before insertion\n- Use parameterized queries to prevent SQL injection\n- Consider using stored procedures for complex insertion logic\n- Test with representative data volumes',4,60,60,'text'),(17,'Update data in a single table','Modify existing records.','# Updating Data\n\nThe UPDATE statement modifies existing data in a table, allowing you to change values in one or more columns based on specified conditions.\n\n## Basic Syntax:\n```sql\nUPDATE table_name\nSET column1 = value1, column2 = value2, ...\nWHERE condition;\n```\n\n## Key Components:\n\n**SET Clause**:\n- Specifies columns to update and their new values\n- Can update multiple columns in single statement\n- Can use expressions, functions, and subqueries\n\n**WHERE Clause**:\n- Filters which rows to update\n- If omitted, all rows in table are updated\n- Use cautiously to avoid unintended updates\n\n## Practical Examples:\n```sql\n-- Update single column with literal value\nUPDATE employees \nSET salary = 60000 \nWHERE employee_id = 101;\n\n-- Update multiple columns\nUPDATE products \nSET price = 29.99, discount = 0.1 \nWHERE product_id = 205;\n\n-- Update with expression\nUPDATE orders \nSET total_amount = quantity * unit_price \nWHERE order_id = 1001;\n\n-- Update with current date/time\nUPDATE users \nSET last_login = CURRENT_TIMESTAMP \nWHERE username = \'johndoe\';\n\n-- Update with subquery\nUPDATE employees \nSET department_id = (\n    SELECT department_id \n    FROM departments \n    WHERE department_name = \'Sales\'\n)\nWHERE employee_id = 102;\n\n-- Update based on another table\nUPDATE inventory i\nSET i.stock_quantity = i.stock_quantity - o.quantity\nFROM orders o\nWHERE i.product_id = o.product_id\nAND o.order_id = 1001;\n\n-- Update with CASE statement\nUPDATE products \nSET price = \n    CASE \n        WHEN category = \'Electronics\' THEN price * 1.1\n        WHEN category = \'Books\' THEN price * 0.9\n        ELSE price\n    END;\n\n-- Incrementing values\nUPDATE counters \nSET value = value + 1 \nWHERE counter_name = \'page_views\';\n\n-- Update with JOIN (variation by database)\nUPDATE employees e\nJOIN departments d ON e.department_id = d.department_id\nSET e.salary = e.salary * 1.05\nWHERE d.location = \'New York\';\n```\n\n## Special Considerations:\n\n**Constraints**:\n- UPDATE must satisfy all constraints\n- Foreign key constraints may restrict or cascade updates\n\n**Triggers**:\n- UPDATE operations may fire triggers\n- Be aware of trigger behavior\n\n**Transaction Control**:\n- Use transactions for multiple related updates\n- COMMIT to save changes, ROLLBACK to undo\n\n## Performance Considerations:\n- Index columns used in WHERE clause for better performance\n- Test updates on a small subset before applying to entire table\n- For large updates, consider batching or off-peak execution\n- Monitor transaction log growth during large updates\n\n## Safety Measures:\n\n**Backup First**:\n- Backup table or database before major updates\n- Consider using temporary tables for testing\n\n**Test with SELECT**:\n- Test WHERE clause with SELECT first to see affected rows\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM employees WHERE department_id = 5; -- Test first\nUPDATE employees SET salary = salary * 1.1 WHERE department_id = 5;\n```\n\n**Use Transactions**:\n```sql\nBEGIN TRANSACTION;\nUPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - 100 WHERE account_id = 101;\nUPDATE accounts SET balance = balance + 100 WHERE account_id = 202;\nCOMMIT; -- Or ROLLBACK if needed\n```\n\n**Limit Clause**:\n- Some databases support LIMIT with UPDATE\n- Useful for updating in batches\n\n## Best Practices:\n- Always include a WHERE clause unless intentionally updating all rows\n- Use meaningful conditions to target specific records\n- Test updates in development environment first\n- Document complex update logic\n- Consider using version control for data changes',4,45,45,'text'),(18,'Delete data from a single table','Remove unwanted records.','# Deleting Data\n\nThe DELETE statement removes rows from a table, either selectively based on conditions or completely.\n\n## Basic Syntax:\n```sql\nDELETE FROM table_name\nWHERE condition;\n```\n\n## Key Components:\n\n**FROM Clause**:\n- Specifies table from which to delete rows\n\n**WHERE Clause**:\n- Filters which rows to delete\n- If omitted, all rows in table are deleted\n- Use with extreme caution\n\n## Practical Examples:\n```sql\n-- Delete specific rows\nDELETE FROM employees \nWHERE employee_id = 101;\n\n-- Delete with condition\nDELETE FROM orders \nWHERE order_date < \'2020-01-01\';\n\n-- Delete using subquery\nDELETE FROM products \nWHERE category_id IN (\n    SELECT category_id \n    FROM categories \n    WHERE discontinued = 1\n);\n\n-- Delete based on another table\nDELETE FROM customers c\nWHERE NOT EXISTS (\n    SELECT 1 \n    FROM orders o \n    WHERE o.customer_id = c.customer_id\n);\n\n-- Delete with JOIN (syntax varies by database)\nDELETE o\nFROM orders o\nJOIN customers c ON o.customer_id = c.customer_id\nWHERE c.country = \'Canada\';\n\n-- Delete all rows from table (DANGEROUS!)\nDELETE FROM temp_log; -- Removes all rows but keeps table structure\n```\n\n## Special Considerations:\n\n**TRUNCATE TABLE**:\n- Alternative to DELETE without WHERE clause\n- Faster for removing all rows\n- Cannot be rolled back in some databases\n- Resets identity/auto-increment values\n\n```sql\nTRUNCATE TABLE temp_log; -- Remove all rows quickly\n```\n\n**Constraints**:\n- DELETE must satisfy all constraints\n- Foreign key constraints may restrict or cascade deletes\n\n**Triggers**:\n- DELETE operations may fire triggers\n- Be aware of trigger behavior\n\n**Transaction Control**:\n- Use transactions for multiple related deletes\n- COMMIT to save changes, ROLLBACK to undo\n\n## Performance Considerations:\n- Index columns used in WHERE clause for better performance\n- For large deletions, consider batching or off-peak execution\n- TRUNCATE is generally faster than DELETE for removing all rows\n- Monitor transaction log growth during large deletions\n\n## Safety Measures:\n\n**Backup First**:\n- Backup table or database before major deletions\n- Consider using temporary tables for testing\n\n**Test with SELECT**:\n- Test WHERE clause with SELECT first to see affected rows\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM orders WHERE order_date < \'2020-01-01\'; -- Test first\nDELETE FROM orders WHERE order_date < \'2020-01-01\';\n```\n\n**Use Transactions**:\n```sql\nBEGIN TRANSACTION;\nDELETE FROM order_items WHERE order_id = 1001;\nDELETE FROM orders WHERE order_id = 1001;\nCOMMIT; -- Or ROLLBACK if needed\n```\n\n**Soft Deletes**:\n- Consider using a \"deleted\" flag instead of physical deletion\n- Allows data recovery and maintains referential integrity\n\n```sql\n-- Instead of DELETE\nUPDATE customers SET is_deleted = 1 WHERE customer_id = 101;\n\n-- Query active records\nSELECT * FROM customers WHERE is_deleted = 0;\n```\n\n**Limit Clause**:\n- Some databases support LIMIT with DELETE\n- Useful for deleting in batches\n\n```sql\n-- MySQL example of batch deletion\nDELETE FROM large_table WHERE condition LIMIT 1000;\n```\n\n## Best Practices:\n- Always include a WHERE clause unless intentionally deleting all rows\n- Use meaningful conditions to target specific records\n- Test deletes in development environment first\n- Consider using soft delete pattern when appropriate\n- Document delete operations, especially in production\n- Implement proper backup and recovery procedures\n\n## Recovery Options:\n- Database backups\n- Transaction log backups\n- Binary logs (MySQL)\n- Flashback technology (Oracle)\n- Always have a recovery plan before performing major deletions',4,30,30,'text'),(19,'Troubleshoot data object management query failures','Resolve errors in table, view, or index operations.','# Troubleshooting Data Object Management\n\nCommon issues and solutions when creating, altering, or dropping database objects like tables, views, and indexes.\n\n## Common Error Categories:\n\n**Syntax Errors**:\n- Incorrect SQL syntax\n- Missing or extra keywords\n- Improper punctuation\n\n**Permission Issues**:\n- Insufficient privileges to create/modify objects\n- Ownership conflicts\n\n**Constraint Violations**:\n- Foreign key constraints\n- Unique constraints\n- Check constraints\n\n**Resource Limitations**:\n- Storage space exhaustion\n- Memory limitations\n- Connection limits\n\n## Specific Issues and Solutions:\n\n### 1. \"Table already exists\" Error:\n**Problem**:\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE employees (id INT, name VARCHAR(50));\n-- Error: Table \'employees\' already exists\n```\n\n**Solutions**:\n```sql\n-- Check if table exists first\nIF NOT EXISTS (SELECT * FROM information_schema.tables \n               WHERE table_name = \'employees\')\nBEGIN\n    CREATE TABLE employees (id INT, name VARCHAR(50));\nEND\n\n-- Or use CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS (if supported)\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS employees (id INT, name VARCHAR(50));\n\n-- Or drop table first (DANGEROUS - will lose data!)\nDROP TABLE IF EXISTS employees;\nCREATE TABLE employees (id INT, name VARCHAR(50));\n```\n\n### 2. \"Invalid column name\" Error:\n**Problem**:\n```sql\nALTER TABLE employees ADD COLUMN phone_number VARCHAR(15);\n-- Error: Invalid column name \'phone_number\'\n```\n\n**Solutions**:\n- Check for typos in column name\n- Verify table name is correct\n- Ensure you have ALTER permission on the table\n\n### 3. \"Foreign key constraint fails\" Error:\n**Problem**:\n```sql\nDROP TABLE departments;\n-- Error: Cannot delete or update a parent row: a foreign key constraint fails\n```\n\n**Solutions**:\n```sql\n-- First drop the foreign key constraint\nALTER TABLE employees DROP FOREIGN KEY fk_department;\n\n-- Or drop the dependent table first\nDROP TABLE employees;\nDROP TABLE departments;\n\n-- Or use CASCADE (if supported)\nDROP TABLE departments CASCADE;\n```\n\n### 4. \"Syntax error near\" Messages:\n**Problem**:\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE test (id INT, name VARCHAR(50)\n-- Error: Syntax error near \')\n```\n\n**Solutions**:\n- Check for missing closing parentheses\n- Verify comma placement in column lists\n- Ensure proper quoting of identifiers\n\n### 5. \"Permission denied\" Error:\n**Problem**:\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE audit_log (id INT, action VARCHAR(50));\n-- Error: Permission denied\n```\n\n**Solutions**:\n- Contact database administrator for appropriate privileges\n- Use a different schema/database where you have create rights\n- Verify your current role/permissions\n\n### 6. \"Out of storage space\" Error:\n**Problem**:\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE large_table (id INT, data TEXT);\n-- Error: Out of storage space\n```\n\n**Solutions**:\n- Free up disk space\n- Increase storage allocation\n- Use a different tablespace/filegroup with more space\n\n## Diagnostic Techniques:\n\n**Check Database Logs**:\n- Review error logs for detailed messages\n- Look for related errors that might indicate underlying issues\n\n**Use Information Schema**:\n```sql\n-- Check table existence\nSELECT * FROM information_schema.tables \nWHERE table_name = \'your_table\';\n\n-- Check column existence\nSELECT * FROM information_schema.columns \nWHERE table_name = \'your_table\' AND column_name = \'your_column\';\n\n-- Check constraints\nSELECT * FROM information_schema.table_constraints \nWHERE table_name = \'your_table\';\n```\n\n**Test with Simple Examples**:\n- Create minimal test cases to isolate the problem\n- Verify basic functionality before complex operations\n\n**Check Database Version**:\n- Some syntax may be version-specific\n- Verify supported features in your database version\n\n## Prevention Strategies:\n\n**Use Transaction Control**:\n```sql\nBEGIN TRANSACTION;\n-- Make changes here\n-- Verify everything looks correct\nCOMMIT; -- Or ROLLBACK if issues\n```\n\n**Implement Error Handling**:\n```sql\nBEGIN TRY\n    -- Your DDL statements here\nEND TRY\nBEGIN CATCH\n    -- Handle errors here\n    PRINT \'Error: \' + ERROR_MESSAGE();\nEND CATCH\n```\n\n**Version Control for Schema**:\n- Maintain scripts for all schema changes\n- Use migration tools for controlled deployments\n- Test changes in development before production\n\n**Documentation**:\n- Document all schema changes and dependencies\n- Maintain data dictionary of all database objects\n\n## Tools for Troubleshooting:\n- Database management studios (SSMS, pgAdmin, MySQL Workbench)\n- Schema comparison tools\n- Query analyzers and explain plans\n- Monitoring tools for resource usage\n\n## Best Practices:\n- Always backup before major schema changes\n- Test changes in non-production environments first\n- Use consistent naming conventions\n- Document object dependencies\n- Implement proper error handling in scripts\n- Monitor database performance after changes',5,60,60,'text'),(20,'Troubleshoot data retrieval query failures','Fix issues in SELECT and JOIN queries.','# Troubleshooting Data Retrieval Queries\n\nCommon issues and solutions when SELECT queries fail or return unexpected results.\n\n## Common Error Categories:\n\n**Syntax Errors**:\n- Incorrect SQL syntax\n- Missing or misspelled keywords\n- Improper clause ordering\n\n**Semantic Errors**:\n- Invalid object references\n- Incorrect data type usage\n- Improper function usage\n\n**Performance Issues**:\n- Slow query execution\n- Excessive resource consumption\n- Timeout errors\n\n**Data Issues**:\n- Unexpected NULL values\n- Missing or duplicate data\n- Incorrect filtering logic\n\n## Specific Issues and Solutions:\n\n### 1. \"Invalid column name\" Error:\n**Problem**:\n```sql\nSELECT employe_name FROM employees;\n-- Error: Invalid column name \'employe_name\'\n```\n\n**Solutions**:\n- Check for typos in column names\n- Verify table structure:\n```sql\nSELECT column_name FROM information_schema.columns \nWHERE table_name = \'employees\';\n```\n- Use proper delimiters if column names contain special characters\n\n### 2. \"Invalid object name\" Error:\n**Problem**:\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM employes;\n-- Error: Invalid object name \'employes\'\n```\n\n**Solutions**:\n- Check for typos in table names\n- Verify table existence:\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM information_schema.tables \nWHERE table_name = \'employees\';\n```\n- Check database/schema context\n- Verify permissions on the object\n\n### 3. \"Ambiguous column name\" Error:\n**Problem**:\n```sql\nSELECT id FROM employees JOIN departments ON employees.id = departments.manager_id;\n-- Error: Ambiguous column name \'id\'\n```\n\n**Solutions**:\n- Use table aliases and qualify column names:\n```sql\nSELECT employees.id FROM employees JOIN departments ON employees.id = departments.manager_id;\n```\n- Or use unique column aliases:\n```sql\nSELECT employees.id AS emp_id FROM employees JOIN departments ON employees.id = departments.manager_id;\n```\n\n### 4. \"Conversion failed\" Error:\n**Problem**:\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM orders WHERE order_date = \'2023-13-01\';\n-- Error: Conversion failed when converting date from character string\n```\n\n**Solutions**:\n- Use proper date formats:\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM orders WHERE order_date = \'2023-01-13\';\n```\n- Use explicit conversion functions:\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM orders WHERE order_date = CAST(\'2023-01-13\' AS DATE);\n```\n- Check for invalid data in the table\n\n### 5. \"Divide by zero\" Error:\n**Problem**:\n```sql\nSELECT total_sales / number_of_customers AS avg_sale FROM sales_summary;\n-- Error: Divide by zero error\n```\n\n**Solutions**:\n- Use NULLIF to handle division by zero:\n```sql\nSELECT total_sales / NULLIF(number_of_customers, 0) AS avg_sale FROM sales_summary;\n```\n- Or use CASE statement:\n```sql\nSELECT \n    CASE \n        WHEN number_of_customers = 0 THEN NULL \n        ELSE total_sales / number_of_customers \n    END AS avg_sale \nFROM sales_summary;\n```\n\n### 6. Query Returns No Results (When Expected):\n**Problem**:\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM products WHERE price = 19.99;\n-- Returns no rows, but you know matching data exists\n```\n\n**Solutions**:\n- Check for data type mismatches\n- Consider floating-point precision issues:\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM products WHERE ABS(price - 19.99) < 0.001;\n```\n- Check for trailing/leading spaces in text columns:\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM products WHERE TRIM(product_name) = \'Widget\';\n```\n- Verify case sensitivity:\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM products WHERE LOWER(product_name) = LOWER(\'Widget\');\n```\n\n### 7. Query Returns Too Many Results:\n**Problem**:\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM orders WHERE order_date > \'2023-01-01\';\n-- Returns more rows than expected\n```\n\n**Solutions**:\n- Add additional filter conditions\n- Check date ranges and boundaries\n- Verify JOIN conditions aren\'t creating Cartesian products\n- Use DISTINCT to eliminate duplicates\n\n### 8. Performance Issues:\n**Problem**:\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM large_table WHERE non_indexed_column = \'value\';\n-- Query runs very slowly\n```\n\n**Solutions**:\n- Add indexes on frequently searched columns:\n```sql\nCREATE INDEX idx_non_indexed_column ON large_table(non_indexed_column);\n```\n- Limit the number of returned columns:\n```sql\nSELECT id, name FROM large_table WHERE non_indexed_column = \'value\';\n```\n- Use pagination for large result sets:\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM large_table WHERE non_indexed_column = \'value\' LIMIT 100 OFFSET 0;\n```\n\n## Diagnostic Techniques:\n\n**Use EXPLAIN or Execution Plans**:\n```sql\nEXPLAIN SELECT * FROM employees WHERE department_id = 5;\n```\n\n**Test with Subsets**:\n- Run query with LIMIT to test syntax before full execution\n- Test individual components of complex queries\n\n**Check Data Quality**:\n```sql\n-- Look for NULL values\nSELECT COUNT(*) FROM table WHERE column IS NULL;\n\n-- Check for data inconsistencies\nSELECT DISTINCT status FROM orders;\n```\n\n**Verify Filter Logic**:\n- Test WHERE conditions independently\n- Check operator precedence with parentheses\n\n## Prevention Strategies:\n\n**Parameterized Queries**:\n- Use parameters instead of concatenating values\n- Prevents SQL injection and type conversion issues\n\n**Consistent Data Types**:\n- Ensure application and database use compatible data types\n- Establish clear data type standards\n\n**Query Review Process**:\n- Peer review complex queries\n- Use code formatting tools for readability\n\n**Monitoring and Logging**:\n- Implement query logging for performance analysis\n- Set up alerts for long-running queries\n\n## Best Practices:\n- Always test queries with sample data first\n- Use transactions for data exploration\n- Implement proper error handling\n- Document complex query logic\n- Regularly review and optimize frequently used queries\n- Keep statistics updated for query optimization\n\n## Tools for Troubleshooting:\n- Database management studios with visual explain plans\n- Query profiling tools\n- Performance monitoring dashboards\n- Schema comparison tools\n- Data quality assessment tools',5,60,60,'text'),(21,'Troubleshoot data manipulation query failures','Correct errors in INSERT, UPDATE, or DELETE operations.','# Troubleshooting Data Manipulation Queries\n\nCommon issues and solutions when INSERT, UPDATE, or DELETE queries fail or produce unexpected results.\n\n## Common Error Categories:\n\n**Constraint Violations**:\n- Primary key violations\n- Foreign key violations\n- Unique constraint violations\n- Check constraint violations\n- Not null violations\n\n**Data Type Issues**:\n- Type conversion errors\n- Precision and scale problems\n- Date/time format issues\n\n**Permission Problems**:\n- Insufficient privileges for DML operations\n- Ownership conflicts\n\n**Resource Limitations**:\n- Lock contention and deadlocks\n- Transaction log full\n- Storage space exhaustion\n\n## Specific Issues and Solutions:\n\n### 1. \"Primary key violation\" Error:\n**Problem**:\n```sql\nINSERT INTO employees (id, name) VALUES (101, \'John Doe\');\n-- Error: Violation of PRIMARY KEY constraint\n```\n\n**Solutions**:\n- Check for existing record with same primary key:\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM employees WHERE id = 101;\n```\n- Use auto-incrementing keys when appropriate\n- Generate unique keys using appropriate algorithms\n- Use INSERT IGNORE or ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE (MySQL) or MERGE (SQL Server)\n\n### 2. \"Foreign key constraint fails\" Error:\n**Problem**:\n```sql\nINSERT INTO orders (customer_id, amount) VALUES (999, 100.00);\n-- Error: Cannot add or update a child row: a foreign key constraint fails\n```\n\n**Solutions**:\n- Verify the referenced value exists:\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM customers WHERE id = 999;\n```\n- Insert the parent record first\n- Use proper cascade rules in foreign key definitions\n- Temporarily disable constraints if appropriate (and re-enable after)\n\n### 3. \"Cannot insert NULL\" Error:\n**Problem**:\n```sql\nINSERT INTO employees (name, email) VALUES (\'John Doe\', \'john@example.com\');\n-- Error: Cannot insert the value NULL into column \'department_id\'\n```\n\n**Solutions**:\n- Provide values for all NOT NULL columns:\n```sql\nINSERT INTO employees (name, email, department_id) \nVALUES (\'John Doe\', \'john@example.com\', 1);\n```\n- Use DEFAULT constraints where appropriate\n- Modify table to allow NULL if business rules permit\n\n### 4. \"String or binary data would be truncated\" Error:\n**Problem**:\n```sql\nINSERT INTO products (name) VALUES (\'Very long product name that exceeds column length\');\n-- Error: String or binary data would be truncated\n```\n\n**Solutions**:\n- Check column length and adjust data accordingly:\n```sql\nSELECT character_maximum_length \nFROM information_schema.columns \nWHERE table_name = \'products\' AND column_name = \'name\';\n```\n- Truncate the value to fit within column limits\n- Consider altering the column to accommodate longer values\n\n### 5. \"Conversion failed\" Error:\n**Problem**:\n```sql\nUPDATE employees SET salary = \'not a number\' WHERE id = 101;\n-- Error: Conversion failed when converting varchar to numeric\n```\n\n**Solutions**:\n- Ensure data types match column definitions\n- Use explicit casting when necessary:\n```sql\nUPDATE employees SET salary = CAST(\'50000\' AS DECIMAL(10,2)) WHERE id = 101;\n```\n- Validate data before insertion/update\n\n### 6. \"Deadlock\" Error:\n**Problem**:\n```sql\nUPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - 100 WHERE account_id = 101;\n-- Error: Transaction was deadlocked on lock resources\n```\n\n**Solutions**:\n- Implement retry logic in application code\n- Access tables in consistent order across transactions\n- Use lower isolation levels when appropriate\n- Keep transactions short and focused\n- Use query hints to control locking behavior\n\n### 7. \"Timeout\" Error:\n**Problem**:\n```sql\nDELETE FROM large_table WHERE condition;\n-- Error: Timeout expired\n```\n\n**Solutions**:\n- Break operation into smaller batches:\n```sql\nWHILE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM large_table WHERE condition)\nBEGIN\n    DELETE TOP (1000) FROM large_table WHERE condition;\nEND\n```\n- Optimize WHERE clause and add indexes\n- Perform during off-peak hours\n- Increase command timeout setting if appropriate\n\n### 8. \"Transaction log full\" Error:\n**Problem**:\n```sql\nUPDATE very_large_table SET column = value;\n-- Error: The transaction log for database is full\n```\n\n**Solutions**:\n- Break operation into smaller transactions\n- Increase log file size or add additional log files\n- Switch to simple recovery model during bulk operations (if appropriate)\n- Backup and truncate the transaction log\n\n## Diagnostic Techniques:\n\n**Check Constraints**:\n```sql\n-- View table constraints\nSELECT * FROM information_schema.table_constraints \nWHERE table_name = \'your_table\';\n\n-- View check constraints\nSELECT * FROM information_schema.check_constraints;\n```\n\n**Examine Data Discrepancies**:\n```sql\n-- Find values that would violate constraints\nSELECT * FROM table WHERE NOT (check_condition);\n```\n\n**Use Transaction Control for Testing**:\n```sql\nBEGIN TRANSACTION;\n-- Test your DML operation here\nROLLBACK; -- Undo changes for testing\n```\n\n**Check Lock Information**:\n- Use sp_who2 (SQL Server) or similar commands to check for blocking\n- Monitor lock wait times and deadlocks\n\n## Prevention Strategies:\n\n**Data Validation**:\n- Validate data before attempting DML operations\n- Use parameterized queries to prevent type conversion issues\n\n**Error Handling**:\n```sql\nBEGIN TRY\n    BEGIN TRANSACTION;\n    -- Your DML operations here\n    COMMIT TRANSACTION;\nEND TRY\nBEGIN CATCH\n    ROLLBACK TRANSACTION;\n    -- Log error details\n    PRINT \'Error: \' + ERROR_MESSAGE();\nEND CATCH\n```\n\n**Batch Processing**:\n- Process large data changes in batches\n- Use appropriate batch sizes based on system capabilities\n\n**Monitoring**:\n- Monitor transaction log size and growth\n- Set up alerts for constraint violations\n- Track deadlock occurrences\n\n## Best Practices:\n- Always test DML operations in non-production environments first\n- Backup critical data before major changes\n- Use transactions appropriately for atomic operations\n- Implement proper indexing for WHERE clauses in UPDATE/DELETE\n- Consider using soft deletes instead of physical deletes\n- Document data modification procedures and dependencies\n- Establish rollback procedures for critical operations\n\n## Tools for Troubleshooting:\n- Database management studios with activity monitors\n- Transaction log readers\n- Lock monitoring tools\n- Performance monitoring dashboards\n- Data comparison tools for verifying changes',5,60,60,'text');
